From chapter 4 onwards, the scope of the story gets expanded, introducing more characters. Up to that point, the pacing was a tad slow in my opinion. Consider how much happened in chapters 1-3, compared to 4-6, yet despite that, I remember more of what happens in 4-6 better than 1-3.

The interspecies dynamic between the sheep and the goats puts weight on the situation, an actual threat. More tangible goals are discussed and set (ship building and crewing), there is set up and pay off of details (Gouentine dressing in mens clothes) and the interaction between our two protagonists starts coming across as a developing relationship between real people. And you have the setup of the ailing mother, a factor that is not yet been addressed all that much, but is a story thread I hope you don't forget and I think would be a good place to explore.

Only negative I'd say is you do have a tendency to start a new line a tad too often in my opinion. but that is something that isn't happening as much in newer chapters, so I think you're subconsciously recognizing where the flow of your story is.
